Regarding their chemical composition, 

Bostrychia
spp.

are reported to produce fatty acids, amino acids, carbohydrates, polysaccharides, betaines, phenolics, and mycosporine-like amino acids (MAAs) (

, 2012; 

; 

, 

; 

). For 

B. calliptera

, there are only a few studies on its specialised metabolites, including volatile constituents (

) and the occurrence of three MAAs, namely porphyra-334, palythine and palythinol (

). As with most 

Bostrychia
species

, the low molecular weight carbohydrates sorbitol, dulcitol and, less commonly, digeneaside can be found in 

B. calliptera
(
Zuccarello and West, 2011
)

.

MAAs are water-soluble ampholytes of low molecular weight, which are composed of a cyclohexenone or cyclohexenimine chromophore substituted by amino acids or other moieties (

). They have been isolated from marine bacteria, fungi, several animals and plants (

) and they possess photoprotective and antioxidant properties (

).

Brominated and sulphated phenols, are phenols substituted with one or more bromine and sulfate residues, respectively (

). They are widely distributed among red (

), brown (

), and green macroalgae (

; 

), but occur also in ascidians, sponges and other animals (

). Their ecological role is not yet clear but brominated and sulphated phenols may contribute in chemical defense and deterrence and play a role as a storage 
form for
more active metabolites (

; 

).

